			<p>The drink stations at most weddings are predictable. Bar with cocktails. Maybe a champagne toast. Coffee at the end if anyone's still standing. But for South Asian weddings, this misses the most quietly powerful beverage of all: chai. After catering hundreds of Vancouver weddings, we've learned that the couples who add a live chai bar — alongside specialty coffee — create the most memorable beverage experiences. Here's why both belong at your wedding.</p>

			<h2>Chai Is <em>More Than a Drink</em></h2>

			<p>For South Asian families, chai is an emotion. It's the morning ritual. It's how grandmothers welcome guests. It's the cup that lingers longest at every family gathering. Serving fresh masala chai at a wedding isn't just a beverage choice — it's a cultural anchor. It tells your guests, especially the older generation, that you've thought about them.</p>

			<p>A live chai bar takes this further. Chai brewed fresh on-site in copper urns, with the spices steeping in front of guests, fills the air with cardamom and ginger. You can smell it before you taste it. That sensory layer is something a buffet beverage line simply cannot deliver.</p>

			<h2>Coffee Has Its <em>Moments Too</em></h2>

			<p>Not every guest grew up with chai. Many guests — especially younger crowds, mixed-cultural attendees, and post-dinner energy needs — gravitate toward specialty coffee. A barista station with espresso, lattes, and pour-overs adds the kind of café-quality beverage experience that makes a wedding feel more current and more thoughtful.</p>

			<p>Pair the two stations and you cover every preference. Older guests gather at the chai bar. Younger guests order cortados. Everyone gets to choose, and everyone feels considered.</p>

			<h2>The <em>Best Moments</em> for Chai &amp; Coffee Stations</h2>

			<h3>Morning Ceremonies</h3>
			<p>Mehndi mornings, haldi rituals, and early ceremony events benefit hugely from a chai bar. Family members are arriving on different schedules, the day starts slowly, and chai keeps the energy warm without overwhelming guests with food too early.</p>

			<h3>Sangeet Pre-Dinner</h3>
			<p>While guests mingle and the music starts, a chai station offers a softer alternative to the bar. It also gives non-drinking guests something special to gather around — they're not just clutching water bottles while everyone else has cocktails.</p>

			<h3>Reception Dessert &amp; Coffee Bar</h3>
			<p>This is where coffee really earns its keep. A late-night barista station alongside the dessert spread keeps energy up for dancing, sends guests off feeling well-cared-for, and turns the typical "coffee in a chafing dish carafe" into a genuine experience.</p>

			<h3>Late-Night Chai</h3>
			<p>Towards the end of the night, when guests are slowing down but not ready to leave, a live chai station works magic. It signals "we're not rushing you out" and gives people a reason to linger, talk, and decompress.</p>

			<h2>What Live Stations Look Like — <em>In Practice</em></h2>

			<p>A live chai bar typically includes a copper urn or handi for brewing, a barista or chai master to serve, and small ceramic cups for guests. Spice variations (cardamom-heavy, ginger-forward, kashmiri pink) can be offered side by side. Add small bites — masala biscuits, koliyada, savoury crackers — and the station becomes a moment guests photograph and remember.</p>

			<p>A specialty coffee bar uses a portable espresso machine, single-origin beans, plant-based milk options, and syrups for customisation. The barista becomes part of the entertainment — guests engage with them, ask for recommendations, and treat the station like a high-end café experience embedded into the wedding.</p>

			<h2>Why Sula Café Brings Both</h2>

			<p>We built <a href="/cafe-catering">Sula Café Catering</a> specifically for moments like these. The same chai we brew daily at our café in East Vancouver, brewed fresh at your wedding. The same baristas. The same ingredients. The same warmth. Pair it with our specialty coffee service and you get a beverage program that feels like an extension of the city's best café — not a hotel buffet line.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>

			<p>The drink station at your wedding doesn't have to be an afterthought. Chai and coffee — done well — can become some of the most memorable, photographed, and talked-about parts of the day. They cost less than most people expect. They serve every demographic at the wedding. And they create the small moments of warmth that turn a wedding into a memory.</p>

			<p>If you'd like to add a chai bar, coffee station, or both to your Vancouver wedding, <a href="https://sulaindianrestaurant.com/request-a-quote/">request a quote</a> from Sula Café Catering and we'll walk you through what works best for your event.</p>

